															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/jacob-conwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1372582); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1372582&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250138" alt="Jacob Conwell" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1372582)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/jacob-conwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1372582); return false;" >Jacob Conwell</a></span> <span class="odate time_1480625473 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Dec 2016 20:51</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2701575">
									

<p>Holy word count, batman!</p>
<p>Despite its length, I never felt that the story dragged, and all the flashbacks provided for great characterization of why Ralph became the person he is. Additionally, Dr. Vang was a pretty compelling villain, especially with his seeming mastery of setting up congnitohazard traps.</p>
<p>Finally, there place where this tale shines, in my opinion is the banter between all these characters. From Conwell and Ralph being the two dorks who could, to Dr. Vang shouting about his &quot;weaponized memes&quot; there were a lot of gems in the dialogue.</p>
<p>+1. Definitely worth the read.</p>

							</div>

								
					
